Show HN: Go Program for Effortlessly Creating Google Meetings from Terminal
text:
I use Google Meetings quite often for ad-hoc conversations and pair programming sessions and I hate to go through all the buttons in the Gmail UI to create these meeting rooms and copy the link.

For this reason, I've create a Go program that uses the Google Calendar API for creating instant meetings with single command on the terminal and copy the link to my clipboard.

Please have a look and if you have any feedback that I can use to improve this program, please share it!

Ask HN: Does your hobby have an “old web” Bible forgotten by search engines?
text:
Looking for one-person, data driven, documentation webpages on DIY, repair, cooking, and other hobbies.

Hard to precisely describe, so I'll go by example:

- Sheldon Brown's Bicycle Technical Info, the online bible for bicyclist [1]

- Guerrilla guide to CNC and resin casting, incredibly documented ressource to get stated in casting [2]

- Jeff Varasano's Famous New York Pizza Recipe, or everything about making pizza at home [3]

Any such foundational webpage for your hobby?

[1]https://www.sheldonbrown.com/

[2]https://lcamtuf.coredump.cx/gcnc/

[3]https://www.varasanos.com/PizzaRecipe.htm

Ask HN: Why is the AI black box such a big deal?
text:
I’ve heard many people say that the unexplainable nature of AI/ML models makes them untrustworthy, but do developers really care in practice? From my experience it seems like all that matters is performance considerations (eg accuracy, data efficiency, mode size, etc). And the field seems to have been progressing fine despite the “black box”.

What would ideal explainability even look like? For example, in deep learning if we knew what individual neurons were doing, would this solve any problems? Or even if we could specifically know why the model makes a particular error, the solution is still just to throw more training data at the model. Maybe increased explainability could help with more rational design of model architectures and training methods, but that has never been such a huge bottleneck in my experience.

SHAP, LIME, saliency maps, and the like I have always felt to be pretty hand wavy, inaccurate, and they don’t provide much insight for what developers need. I feel like they only exist to placate AI/ML skeptics so we can claim we sort of know what is going on with our models only when someone cares.

Am I missing something here? What specific efficiencies or insights would a developer benefit from if we had more explainable AI/ML models?
